  m= 100: (1/π)∫_0^π log(1+F_m(θ))dθ = 1.166139, val/log(m) = 0.253224, val/(2logφ) = 1.211669
  m= 500: (1/π)∫_0^π log(1+F_m(θ))dθ = 1.166239, val/log(m) = 0.187661, val/(2logφ) = 1.211773
  m=1000: (1/π)∫_0^π log(1+F_m(θ))dθ = 1.166234, val/log(m) = 0.168830, val/(2logφ) = 1.211767

Observation: the integral grows as 2·log(m) + const, not 2·log(φ)!
This is because logF_p ≈ 2m·logφ but the RIEMANN SUM has m terms,
each contributing ~2logφ/1 in the average, while the INTEGRAL is
dominated by the peak at θ=0 which contributes ~log(m²).

The resolution: the Riemann sum ≠ integral for sharply peaked functions.
The peak of F_m at θ=0 has width O(1/m), capturing ~O(1) sample points
near θ=0, each contributing O(log m²). But there are ~m points total,
each contributing O(1) on average.

